<HEADLINE> German Loans for Three Gorges Dam of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The gigantic Three Gorges
power project in the middle reaches of the Yangtze River has
received more than 270 million U.S. dollars in loans from German
banks for purchase of 14 turbines and generators, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Bank (SDB) of China, which is responsible
for raising overseas funds for the project, yesterday signed
agreements on the lending of loans in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Germany's KFW, Dresdner Bank, Commerz Bank,
DG Bank, the Voith-GE-Siemens consortium, and the China Yangtze
Three Gorges Dam Development Corporation were present at the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The loan package comes in two parts: the first is 71.41 million
U.S. dollars as export credits with a 21-year term and 9-year
grace period, while the second is 200 million U.S. dollars in
commercial loans with a 17-year term and 9-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used to purchase equipment and technology for
the project from the Voith-GE-Siemens consortium, which has won
the contracts to supply six of the dam's 14 power generators.
</P>
<P>
The Anglo-French group GEC Alsthom and ABB Power Generation of
Switzerland received the contracts to provide the remaining eight
generating units.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign loans involved in the contracts amount to 1.1
billion U.S. dollars, including 600 million U.S. dollars in export
credits and 500 million U.S. dollars in commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
The SDB will help the China Yangtze Three Gorges Dam Development
Corp reach other detailed loan contracts in the days ahead, said the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam, which will require a total investment of
200 billion yuan, is scheduled to start generating electricity in
2003 and will be fully completed in 2009. 
</P>
